{{good article}}
[[File:Roman Wall painting from the House of Giuseppe II, Pompeii, 1st century AD, death of Sophonisba, but more likely Cleopatra VII of Egypt consuming poison.jpg|thumb|400px|[[Roman art|Roman painting]] from the House of Giuseppe II, [[Pompeii]], early 1st century AD, most likely depicting [[Cleopatra VII]], wearing her royal [[diadem]], consuming poison in an act of suicide, while her son [[Caesarion]], also wearing a royal diadem, stands behind her{{sfnp|Roller|2010|pp=178–179}}{{sfnp|Elia|1956|pp=3–7}}]]
{{Cleopatra}}

The '''death of Cleopatra VII''', the last reigning ruler of [[Ptolemaic Egypt]], occurred on either 10 or 12 August 30 BC in [[Alexandria]], when she was 39 years old. According to a popular belief, [[Cleopatra]] committed suicide by allowing an [[Asp (reptile)|asp]] ([[Egyptian cobra]]) to bite her. According to [[Greek historiography|Greek]] and [[Roman historiography|Roman historians]], Cleopatra [[Poisoning|poisoned]] herself using either a [[Neurotoxin|toxic]] ointment or sharp implement such as a hairpin. [[Primary source]] accounts are derived mainly from the works of the ancient Roman historians [[Strabo]], [[Plutarch]], and [[Cassius Dio]]. Modern scholars debate the validity of ancient reports involving snakebites as the cause of death and even if she was murdered or not. Some academics hypothesize that her [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] political rival [[Octavian]] forced her to commit suicide in the manner of her choosing. The location of [[Tomb of Antony and Cleopatra|Cleopatra's tomb]] is unknown, although it was recorded that Octavian allowed for her and husband [[Mark Antony]], who stabbed himself with a sword, to be [[Ancient Greek funeral and burial practices|buried together properly]].

Cleopatra's death effectively ended [[Final War of the Roman Republic|the final war]] of the [[Roman Republic]] between [[Second Triumvirate|triumvirs]] Octavian and Antony, in which Cleopatra aligned herself with Antony, father to three of her children. Antony and Cleopatra fled to Egypt following their loss at the 31 BC [[Battle of Actium]] in [[Roman Greece]], after which Octavian invaded Egypt and defeated their forces. Her suicide allowed her to avoid the humiliation of being paraded as a prisoner in a [[Roman triumph]] celebrating the [[Wars of Augustus|military victories of Octavian]], who would become [[Roman emperor|Rome's first emperor]] in 27 BC and known as [[Augustus]]. Octavian had her son Caesarion (also known as [[Ptolemy XV]]), rival heir of [[Julius Caesar]], killed in Egypt but spared her children with Antony and brought them to [[Rome]]. Cleopatra's death marked the end of the [[Hellenistic period]] and [[Ptolemaic dynasty|Ptolemaic rule]] of [[History of Egypt|Egypt]], as well as the beginning of [[Roman Egypt]], which became a [[Roman province|province]] of the [[Roman Empire]].<ref group="note" name="Grant Hellenistic period explanation">{{harvnb|Grant|1972|pp=5–6}} notes that the [[Hellenistic period]], beginning with the reign of [[Alexander the Great]] (336–323 BC), came to an end with the death of Cleopatra in 30 BC. [[Michael Grant (classicist)|Michael Grant]] stresses that the [[Hellenistic Greece|Hellenistic Greeks]] were viewed by contemporary Romans as having declined and diminished in greatness since the age of [[Classical Greece]], an attitude that has continued even into the works of modern [[historiography]]. In regards to [[Hellenistic Egypt]], Grant argues that "Cleopatra VII, looking back upon all that her ancestors had done during that time, was not likely to make the same mistake. But she and her contemporaries of the first century BC had another, peculiar, problem of their own. Could the '[[Hellenistic Age]]' (which we ourselves often regard as coming to an end in about her time) still be said to exist at all, could ''any'' Greek age, now that [[Roman Republic|the Romans]] were the dominant power? This was a question never far from Cleopatra's mind. But it is quite certain that she considered the Greek epoch to be by no means finished, and intended to do everything in her power to ensure its perpetuation."</ref> 

The death of Cleopatra has been depicted in [[List of cultural depictions of Cleopatra|various works of art]] in ancient, medieval, early modern, and modern times. These include the visual, literary, and performance arts, ranging from sculptures and paintings to poetry and plays, as well as modern films. Cleopatra featured prominently in the prose and poetry of ancient [[Latin literature]]. While surviving [[Roman art|ancient Roman]] depictions of her death in visual arts are rare, [[Medieval art|Medieval]], [[Renaissance art|Renaissance]], [[Baroque art|Baroque]], and [[Modern art|Modern]] works are numerous. Ancient [[Greco-Roman]] [[Roman sculpture|sculptures]] such as the ''[[Esquiline Venus]]'' and ''[[Sleeping Ariadne]]'' served as inspirations for later artworks portraying her death, universally involving the snakebite of an asp. Cleopatra's death has also involved themes of [[eroticism]] and sexuality, in works that include paintings, plays, and films, especially from the [[Victorian era]]. Modern works depicting Cleopatra's death include [[Neoclassical sculpture]], [[Orientalist painting]], and cinema.

==Prelude==
{{further|Final War of the Roman Republic|Battle of Actium||Early life of Cleopatra|Reign of Cleopatra}}
[[File:Cleopatra Tetradrachm Antiochia.jpg|thumb|300px|Cleopatra and Mark Antony on the obverse and reverse, respectively, of a silver [[tetradrachm]] struck at the [[Antioch on the Orontes|Antioch]] mint in 36 BC]]

Following the [[First Triumvirate]] and [[assassination of Julius Caesar]] in 44 BC, the Roman statesmen [[Octavian]], [[Mark Antony]], and [[Marcus Aemilius Lepidus (triumvir)|Aemilius Lepidus]] were [[Elections in the Roman Republic|elected]] as [[triumvirate|triumvir]]s to [[Liberators' civil war|bring Caesar's assassins to justice]], forming the [[Second Triumvirate]].{{sfnp|Roller|2010|p=75}}{{sfnp|Burstein|2004|pp=xxi, 21–22}} With Lepidus marginalized in [[Africa (Roman province)|Africa]] and eventually placed under house arrest by Octavian,{{sfnp|Bringmann|2007|p=301}}{{sfnp|Roller|2010|p=98}}{{sfnp|Burstein|2004|p=27}} the two remaining triumvirs divided control over the Roman world between the [[Greek East and Latin West]], with Antony taking the former and Octavian the latter.{{sfnp|Grant|Badian|2018|}}{{sfnp|Roller|2010|p=76}} [[Cleopatra VII]] of [[Ptolemaic Egypt]], a pharaoh of [[Macedon]]ian [[Ancient Greece|Greek]] descent, ruling from Alexandria,{{sfnp|Roller|2010|pp=15–16}}{{sfnp|Jones|2006|pp=xiii, 3, 279}}{{sfnp|Southern|2009|p=43}} had an extramarital affair with [[Julius Caesar]] that produced a son and eventual [[List of Ptolemaic rulers|Ptolemaic]] co-ruler [[Caesarion]].{{sfnp|Bringmann|2007|p=260}}{{sfnp|Fletcher|2008|pp=162–163}}{{sfnp|Jones|2006|p=xiv}} After Caesar's death she developed a relationship with Antony.{{sfnp|Grant|Badian|2018|}}{{sfnp|Roller|2010|pp=76–84}}{{sfnp|Burstein|2004|pp=xxii, 25}} 

With encouragement from Cleopatra, Antony officially divorced Octavian's sister [[Octavia Minor]] in 32 BC.{{sfnp|Roller|2010|p=135}}{{sfnp|Bringmann|2007|p=303}}{{sfnp|Burstein|2004|pp=xxii, 29}} However, it is likely he had already married Cleopatra during the [[Donations of Alexandria]] in 34 BC.{{sfnp|Roller|2010|p=100}}{{sfnp|Burstein|2004|pp=xxii, 29}}<ref group="note">{{harvtxt|Roller|2010|p=100}} says that it is unclear if Antony and Cleopatra were ever truly married. {{harvtxt|Burstein|2004|pp=xxii, 29}} says that the marriage publicly sealed Antony's alliance with Cleopatra and in defiance of Octavian he would divorce Octavia in 32 BC. Coins of Antony and Cleopatra depict them in the typical manner of a Hellenistic royal couple, as explained by {{harvtxt|Roller|2010|p=100}}.</ref> Antony's divorce from Octavia, Octavian's public revelation of Antony's will outlining Cleopatra's ambitions for Roman territory in the Donations of Alexandria and her continued illegal military support for a [[Roman citizenship|Roman citizen]] currently without an elected office convinced the [[Roman Senate]], now under Octavian's control,{{sfnp|Roller|2010|p=134}}{{sfnp|Bringmann|2007|pp=302–303}}{{sfnp|Burstein|2004|pp=29–30}} to [[Final War of the Roman Republic|declare war on Cleopatra]].{{sfnp|Roller|2010|pp=136–137}}{{sfnp|Burstein|2004|pp=xxii, 30}}{{sfnp|Jones|2006|p=147}}

Following their defeat in the naval [[Battle of Actium]] at the [[Ambracian Gulf]] of Greece in 31 BC, Cleopatra and Antony retreated back to Egypt to recuperate and prepare for an assault by Octavian, whose forces grew larger with the surrender of many of Antony's officers and soldiers in Greece.{{sfnp|Roller|2010|p=140}}{{sfnp|Burstein|2004|pp=xxii–xxiii, 30–31}}{{sfnp|Bringmann|2007|p=304}}<ref group="note">For further validation, see {{harvnb|Southern|2009|pp=149–150}} and {{harvnb|Grout|2017}}.</ref> After a long period of failed negotiations, Octavian's forces invaded Egypt in the spring of 30 BC.{{sfnp|Burstein|2004|pp=xxiii, 31}}{{sfnp|Roller|2010|pp=144–145}} While Octavian captured [[Pelousion]] near the eastern borders of Ptolemaic Egypt, his officer [[Cornelius Gallus]] marched from [[Cyrene, Libya|Cyrene]] and captured [[Mersa Matruh|Paraitonion]] to the west.{{sfnp|Roller|2010|p=145}}{{sfnp|Southern|2009|p=153}} Although Antony was able to score a small victory over Octavian's tired troops as they approached Alexandria's [[hippodrome]] on 1 August 30 BC, Antony's naval fleet and cavalry defected to Octavian soon afterwards.{{sfnp|Roller|2010|p=145}}{{sfnp|Bringmann|2007|p=304}}{{sfnp|Southern|2009|pp=153–154}}

==Suicide of Antony and Cleopatra==
{{further|Reign of Cleopatra}}
{{Multiple image
|total_width=400
|image1=Cleopatra VII, dalla via appia tra ariccia e genzano, 40-30 ac ca. 01.JPG
|image2=Cleopatra VII Philopator, engraving by Élisabeth Sophie Chéron after a Hellenistic medallion, published c. 1736.jpg
|footer=Left: the [[commons:Category:Bust of Cleopatra VII in the Altes Museum Berlin|Berlin Cleopatra]], a [[Roman sculpture|Roman bust]] of Cleopatra VII wearing a royal [[diadem]], mid-1st century BC, [[Altes Museum]], [[Antikensammlung Berlin]]{{sfnp|Pina Polo|2013|pp=184–186}}{{sfnp|Roller|2010|pp=54, 174–175}} {{pb}}Right: an [[engraving]] depicting Cleopatra VII by French artist [[Élisabeth Sophie Chéron]] (1648-1711), based on a [[medallion]] of Cleopatra dated to the [[Hellenistic period]] of antiquity
}}

With Octavian's forces in Alexandria, Cleopatra withdrew to her tomb with her closest attendants and had a message sent to Antony that she had committed suicide. Antony ordered his slave Eros to murder him, but instead Eros turned his sword on himself and committed suicide.{{sfnp|Southern|2009|p=154}}{{sfnp|Jones|2006|p=184}} In despair, Antony stabbed himself through the stomach with a sword, dying at age 53.{{sfnp|Roller|2010|p=145}}{{sfnp|Bringmann|2007|p=304}}{{sfnp|Burstein|2004|p=31}} In [[Plutarch]]'s telling, Antony was still alive as he was carried into the tomb of Cleopatra, telling her in his dying words that he would die honorably and that she could trust a certain [[:de:Gaius Proculeius|Gaius Proculeius]] on Octavian's side to treat her well.{{sfnp|Roller|2010|p=145}}{{sfnp|Southern|2009|pp=154–155}}{{sfnp|Jones|2006|pp=184–185}} The same Proculeius used a ladder to breach a window of Cleopatra's tomb and detain her inside before she could have a chance to commit suicide or burn herself to death along with her vast treasure.{{sfnp|Roller|2010|p=145}}{{sfnp|Jones|2006|pp=185–186}} Cleopatra was allowed to [[embalm]] Antony's body before she was forcefully escorted to the palace and eventually met with Octavian, who had also detained three of her children: [[Alexander Helios]], [[Cleopatra Selene II]], and [[Ptolemy Philadelphus (son of Cleopatra)|Ptolemy Philadelphus]].{{sfnp|Burstein|2004|p=31}}{{sfnp|Roller|2010|p=146}}{{sfnp|Southern|2009|p=155}}

As related by [[Livy]], in her meeting with Octavian, Cleopatra told him candidly, "I will not be led in a triumph" ({{lang-grc|οὑ θριαμβεύσομαι|ou thriambéusomai}}), but Octavian only gave the cryptic answer that her life would be spared.{{sfnp|Roller|2010|pp=146–147, 213 footnote83}}{{sfnp|Gurval|2011|p=61}} He did not offer her any specific details about his plans for Egypt or her royal family.{{sfnp|Roller|2010|pp=146–147}} When a spy informed Cleopatra that Octavian intended to bring her back to [[Rome]] to be paraded as a prisoner in his [[Roman triumph]], she decided to avoid this humiliation and take her own life at age 39, in August 30 BC.{{sfnp|Bringmann|2007|p=304}}{{sfnp|Roller|2010|pp=147–148}}{{sfnp|Burstein|2004|pp=xxiii, 31–32}}<ref group="note">For further validation, see {{harvnb|Jones|2006|p=180}} and {{harvnb|Grout|2017}}.</ref> Plutarch elaborates how Cleopatra approached her suicide in an almost ritual process, preceded by bathing and then a fine meal including figs brought to her in a basket.{{sfnp|Roller|2010|p=147}}{{sfnp|Anderson|2003|p=56}}{{sfnp|Jones|2006|p=194}}

Plutarch writes that Octavian ordered his freedman [[Epaphroditus (freedman of Augustus)|Epaphroditus]] to guard her and prevent her from committing suicide.{{sfnp|Plutarch|1920|p=79}} However, Cleopatra was able to deceive him and kill herself nevertheless.{{sfnp|Plutarch|1920|p=79}} When Octavian received a note from Cleopatra requesting that she be buried next to Antony, he had his messengers rush to her. On arrival, in haste, the servant broke down her door but was too late.{{sfnp|Roller|2010|p=147}} Plutarch states that when she was found, her handmaiden Iras dying at her feet, and handmaiden [[Charmion (servant to Cleopatra)|Charmion]] adjusting Cleopatra's [[diadem]]ed crown before she herself fell.{{sfnp|Roller|2010|p=147}}{{sfnp|Anderson|2003|pp=56, 62}}{{sfnp|Gurval|2011|p=72}}<ref group="note">For primary source translations of Plutarch's account of the deaths of [[Charmion (servant to Cleopatra)|Charmion and Iras]], see {{harvnb|Plutarch|1920|p=85}}, {{harvnb|Grout|2017}}, and {{harvnb|Jones|2006|pp=193–194}}.</ref> It is unclear from primary sources if their suicides took place within the palace or inside Cleopatra's tomb.{{sfnp|Roller|2010|pp=147–148}} Cassius Dio claims that Octavian called on trained [[snake charmers]] of the [[Psylli]] tribe of [[Ancient Libya]] to attempt an oral [[Snake venom|venom extraction]] and revival of Cleopatra, but their efforts failed.{{sfnp|Grout|2017}}{{sfnp|Jones|2006|p=195}} Although Octavian was outraged by these events and "was robbed of the full splendor of his victory" according to Cassius Dio,{{sfnp|Jones|2006|p=195}} he had Cleopatra interred next to Antony in their tomb as requested, and also gave Iras and Charmion proper burials.{{sfnp|Roller|2010|p=147}}{{sfnp|Burstein|2004|p=65}}{{sfnp|Jones|2006|p=194}}

==Date of death==
{{further|Chronological dating|Ab urbe condita|Olympiad|Epoch (reference date)|Regnal year}}
[[File:0010-Cleopatra-03.jpg|thumb|300px|A [[Ancient Greek coinage|hemiobol coin]] of Cleopatra VII struck in 31 BC (the year she and Mark Antony lost the Battle of Actium), showing her wearing the royal [[diadem]]]]

There is no surviving records dating Cleopatra's death.{{sfnp|Skeat|1953|pp=98–100}} [[Theodore Cressy Skeat]] deduced that she died on 12 August 30 BC on the basis of contemporary records of fixed events along with cross examination of historical sources.{{sfnp|Skeat|1953|pp=98–100}} His supposition is supported by [[Stanley M. Burstein]],{{sfnp|Burstein|2004|p=31}} James Grout,{{sfnp|Grout|2017}} and [[Aidan Dodson]] and Dyan Hitlon, although the latter are more cautious by qualifying it was ''circa'' 12 August.{{sfnp|Dodson|Hilton|2004|p=277}} An alternative date of 10 August 30 BC is supported by scholars such as [[Duane W. Roller]],{{sfnp|Roller|2010|pp=147–148}} [[Joann Fletcher]],{{sfnp|Fletcher|2008|p=3}} and [[Jaynie Anderson]].{{sfnp|Anderson|2003|p=56}}

==Cause of death==
{{further|Roman historiography}}
[[File:Cleopatra_VII,_steel_engraving_of_the_encaustic_painting_found_at_Hadrian%27s_Villa_in_1818.jpg|thumb|left|A [[steel engraving]] depicting Caesar [[Augustus]]' now lost [[Roman art|painting]] of Cleopatra VII in [[Encaustic painting|encaustic]], which was discovered at Emperor [[Hadrian]]'s [[Hadrian's Villa|Villa]] (near [[Tivoli, Lazio|Tivoli]], Italy) in 1818;{{sfnp|Pratt|Fizel|1949|pp=14–15}} she is seen here wearing the golden [[radiant crown]] of the [[List of Ptolemaic rulers|Ptolemaic rulers]],{{sfnp|Sartain|1885|pp=41, 44}} and an [[Tyet|Isis knot]] (corresponding to Plutarch's description of her wearing the robes of [[Isis]]).{{sfnp|Plutarch|1920|p=54}}]]

Cleopatra's personal physician Olympos, [[Parallel Lives|cited by Plutarch]], did not mention either a cause of death and or an [[Asp (reptile)|asp]] bite or [[Egyptian cobra]].{{sfnp|Roller|2010|p=148}}<ref group="note">Historian [[Duane W. Roller]], in {{harvnb|Roller|2010|pp=148–149}}, provides a thorough explanation of the various claims about Cleopatra's [[cause of death]] in [[Roman historiography]] and primary sources. He states unequivocally that Olympos did not describe any cause of death, only that Plutarch discussed the cause of death only after he was finished relaying the report by Olympos, introducing the tale of the asp bite in such a way that he expected his readers to have already had foreknowledge about it. {{harvnb|Maloney|2010|p=3}}, on the other hand, claims that Olympos "theorized" about Cleopatra's cause of death as being caused by an asp bite or toxic ointment.</ref> [[Strabo]], who provides the earliest known historical account, believed that Cleopatra committed suicide either by asp bite or poisonous ointment.{{sfnp|Anderson|2003|p=56}}{{sfnp|Jones|2006|p=197}}{{sfnp|Gurval|2011|p=55}}<ref group="note">For further validation, see {{harvnb|Roller|2010|p=148}}.</ref> Plutarch mentions the tale of the asp brought to her in a basket of figs, although he offers other alternatives for her cause of death, such as use of a hollow implement ({{lang-el|κνηστίς|knestis}}), perhaps a hairpin,{{sfnp|Jones|2006|p=194}} which she used to scratch open the skin and introduce the toxin.{{sfnp|Roller|2010|p=148}} According to Cassius Dio small puncture wounds were found on Cleopatra's arm, but he echoed the claim by Plutarch that nobody knew the true cause of her death.{{sfnp|Jones|2006|pp=194–195}}{{sfnp|Roller|2010|p=148}}{{sfnp|Grout|2017}} Dio mentioned the claim of the asp and even suggested use of a needle ({{lang-el|βελὁνη|belone}}), possibly from a hairpin, which would seem to corroborate with Plutarch's account.{{sfnp|Jones|2006|pp=194–195}}{{sfnp|Roller|2010|p=148}}{{sfnp|Grout|2017}} Other historians such as [[Florus]] and [[Velleius Paterculus]] supported the asp bite version.{{sfnp|Jones|2006|pp=189–190}}{{sfnp|Roller|2010|p=149}} Roman physician [[Galen]] mentioned the asp story,{{sfnp|Roller|2010|p=149}} but he also narrated a version where Cleopatra bit her arm and introduced venom there brought to her in a container.{{sfnp|Jones|2006|pp=195–197}} [[Suetonius]] relayed the story of the asp but expressed doubt about it.{{sfnp|Roller|2010|p=149}}

Modern scholars have also cast doubt on the story of the [[venomous snake]]bite as the cause of death. Duane W. Roller notes the prominence of snakes in [[Egyptian mythology]] while also asserting that no surviving historical account discusses the difficulty of smuggling a large Egyptian cobra into Cleopatra's chambers and then having it behave as intended.{{sfnp|Roller|2010|p=148}} William Maloney concurs with this assessment, noting the incredible weight of these reptiles, but states that their venom is very powerful,{{sfnp|Maloney|2010|p=3}} whereas Roller claims the venom is only fatal if injected into a vital area of the body.{{sfnp|Roller|2010|p=148}} The German [[Egyptologist]] [[Wilhelm Spiegelberg]] (1870–1930) argued that Cleopatra's choice of suicide by asp bite was one that befitted her royal status, with the asp representing the ''[[uraeus]]'', sacred serpent of the [[ancient Egyptian religion|ancient Egyptian]] sun god [[Ra]].{{sfnp|Gurval|2011|p=56}} However, Robert A. Gurval points out that the [[Ancient Athens|Athenian]] ''[[strategos]]'' [[Demetrios of Phaleron]] (c. 350 – c. 280 BC), confined by [[Ptolemy II Philadelphus]] in Egypt, committed suicide by asp bite in a "curiously similar" manner, one that also demonstrated that it was not exclusive to Egyptian royalty.{{sfnp|Gurval|2011|p=58}}<ref group="note">For further validation that [[Demetrios of Phaleron]], adviser to [[Ptolemy I Soter]], died from an asp bite, see {{harvnb|Roller|2010|p=149}}.</ref> Gurval notes that the bite of an Egyptian cobra contains around 175–300&nbsp;mg of [[neurotoxin]], lethal to humans with only 15–20&nbsp;mg, although death would not have been immediate as victims usually stay alive for several hours.{{sfnp|Gurval|2011|p=60}}

According to Gregory Tsoucalas and Markos Sgantzos, evidence suggests that Octavian ordered the poisoning of Cleopatra.{{sfnp|Tsoucalas|Sgantzos|2014|pp=19–20}} Their claim of alleged murder by Octavian is supported by other authors such as Maloney.{{sfnp|Maloney|2010|pp=3–4}} In her ''Murder of Cleopatra: History's Greatest Cold Case'' (2013), the criminal profiler [[Pat Brown (criminal profiler)|Pat Brown]] argues that Cleopatra was murdered and the details of it were covered up by Roman authorities.{{sfnp|Nuwer|2013}} Claims that she was murdered, however, contradict the majority of primary sources that report her cause of death as suicide.{{sfnp|Jones|2006|pp=180–201}} The English historian [[Patricia Southern]] speculates that Octavian could have possibly allowed Cleopatra to choose the manner of her death instead of executing her.{{sfnp|Southern|2009|p=154}} James Grout writes that Octavian may have wanted to avoid the sort of sympathy espoused for Cleopatra's younger sister [[Arsinoe IV]] when she was paraded in chains but spared during [[Military campaigns of Julius Caesar|Julius Caesar's triumph]].{{sfnp|Grout|2017}} Realizing the political problems of killing a queen whose statue had been erected by his adoptive father Caesar in the Temple of [[Venus Genetrix]], Octavian perhaps permitted Cleopatra "to die by her own hand," according to Grout.{{sfnp|Grout|2017}}

==Aftermath==
{{further|History of the Roman Empire|History of Egypt}}
{{multiple image|total_width=500
|image1=Venus and Cupid from the House of Marcus Fabius Rufus at Pompeii, most likely a depiction of Cleopatra VII (2).jpg
|image2=Venus and Cupid from the House of Marcus Fabius Rufus at Pompeii, most likely a depiction of Cleopatra VII (5).jpg
|footer=This mid-1st century BC [[Pompeian Styles|Roman wall painting]] in [[Pompeii]], Italy, showing [[Venus (mythology)|Venus]] holding a [[cupid]] is most likely a depiction of Cleopatra VII of Ptolemaic Egypt as [[Venus Genetrix]], with her son [[Caesarion]] as the cupid, similar in appearance to the now lost statue of Cleopatra erected by Julius Caesar in the [[Temple of Venus Genetrix]] (within the [[Forum of Caesar]]). The owner of the House of Marcus Fabius Rufus at Pompeii walled off the room with this painting, probably an immediate reaction to the execution of Caesarion on orders of Octavian in 30 BC, when artistic depictions of Caesarion would have been considered [[Damnatio memoriae|a sensitive issue]] for the ruling regime.{{sfnp|Roller|2010|p=175}}{{sfnp|Walker|2008|pp=35, 42–44}}
}}

During her final days, Cleopatra had Caesarion sent away to Upper Egypt and perhaps planned for him to eventually flee to [[Nubia]], Ethiopia, or India in exile.{{sfnp|Roller|2010|p=149}}{{sfnp|Burstein|2004|p=32}}{{sfnp|Southern|2009|p=153}} However, Caesarion would reign as Ptolemy XV for only eighteen days, when he was captured and executed on Octavian's orders on 29 August 30 BC.{{sfnp|Roller|2010|pp=149–150}}{{sfnp|Burstein|2004|pp=xxiii, 32}} This was done after the advice given by the Alexandrian [[Ancient Greek philosophy|Greek philosopher]] [[Arius Didymus]], who cautioned that two rival heirs to Julius Caesar could not share the world together.{{sfnp|Roller|2010|pp=149–150}}{{sfnp|Burstein|2004|pp=xxiii, 32}} 

The deaths of Cleopatra and Caesarion marked the end of both the [[Ptolemaic dynasty]]'s rule of Egypt and the [[Hellenistic period]],{{sfnp|Burstein|2004|pp=xxiii, 1}}{{sfnp|Bringmann|2007|pp=304–307}}{{sfnp|Roller|2010|pp=150–151}} which had lasted since the reign of [[Alexander the Great]] (r. 336–323 BC).<ref group="note" name="Grant Hellenistic period explanation"/> [[Roman Egypt|Egypt]] became a [[Roman province|province]] of the [[History of the Roman Empire|newly-established]] [[Roman Empire]], with Octavian [[Constitutional reforms of Augustus|renamed]] in 27 BC as [[Augustus]], the first [[Roman emperor]],{{sfnp|Burstein|2004|pp=xxiii, 1}}{{sfnp|Bringmann|2007|pp=304–307}}{{sfnp|Roller|2010|pp=150–151}}<ref group="note">For further validation, see {{harvnb|Jones|2006|pp=197–198}}.</ref> ruling with the facade of a [[Roman Republic]].{{sfnp|Eder|2005|pp=24–25}} Roller affirms that Caesarion's alleged reign was "essentially a fiction" invented by chroniclers of Egypt, such as [[Clement of Alexandria]] in his ''[[Stromata]]'', to explain the gap between Cleopatra's death and the induction of Egypt as a Roman province directly ruled by Octavian as pharaoh of Egypt.{{sfnp|Roller|2010|pp=149, 151, 214, footnote 103}}<ref group="note">For further information, see {{harvnb|Skeat|1953|pp=99–100}}. <br>Plutarch, translated by {{harvnb|Jones|2006|p=187}}, wrote in vague terms that "Octavian had Caesarion killed later, after Cleopatra's death." <br>Contrary to regular [[Roman province]]s, Octavian established Egypt as territory under his personal control, barring the [[Roman Senate]] from intervening in any of its affairs and appointing his own [[Equites|equestrian]] [[praefectus augustalis|governors of Egypt]], the first of whom was [[Cornelius Gallus]]. For further information, see {{harvnb|Southern|2014|p=185}} and {{harvnb|Roller|2010|p=151}}.</ref> Antony's three children with Cleopatra were spared and sent to Rome; their daughter Cleopatra Selene II eventually married [[Juba II]] of [[Mauretania]].{{sfnp|Southern|2009|p=155}}{{sfnp|Burstein|2004|pp=32, 76–77}}{{sfnp|Roller|2010|pp=153–155}}

==Tomb of Antony and Cleopatra==
{{further|Tomb of Antony and Cleopatra}}
[[File:Marcus Antonius marble bust in the Vatican Museums.jpg|thumb|left|upright|A [[Roman sculpture|Roman marble bust]] of the [[Roman consul|consul]] and triumvir Mark Antony, late 1st century AD, [[Vatican Museums]]]]
The site of the [[Tomb of Antony and Cleopatra|mausoleum of Cleopatra and Mark Antony]] is uncertain.{{sfnp|Southern|2009|p=155}} The [[Egyptian Antiquities Service]] believes that it is in or near a temple of [[Taposiris Magna]], southwest of [[History of Alexandria|Alexandria]].{{sfnp|BBC News}}{{sfnp|SBS News}} In their excavations of the temple of [[Osiris]] at Taposiris Magna, [[People of the Dominican Republic|Dominican]] archaeologist [[Kathleen Martinez]] and Egyptian archaeologist [[Zahi Hawass]] have discovered six burial chambers along with various artifacts, including forty [[Ptolemaic coinage|coins]] minted by Cleopatra and Antony as well as an alabaster bust depicting Cleopatra.{{sfnp|Remezcla}} An alabaster mask with a cleft chin discovered at the site bears a resemblance to ancient portraits of Mark Antony.{{sfnp|Reuters}} In an [[:File:Roman Wall painting from the House of Giuseppe II, Pompeii, 1st century AD, death of Sophonisba, but more likely Cleopatra VII of Egypt consuming poison (2).jpg|early 1st century AD painting]] from the House of Giuseppe II in [[Pompeii]], a rear wall depicted with a set of double doors positioned very high above the scene of a woman wearing a royal diadem and committing suicide among her attendants suggests the described layout of Cleopatra's tomb in Alexandria.{{sfnp|Roller|2010|pp=178–179}}

==Depictions in art and literature==
{{further|List of cultural depictions of Cleopatra|Cleopatra#Cultural depictions}}

===Hellenistic and Roman eras===
{{further|Hellenistic art|Roman art|Roman portraiture|Ancient Egyptian art|Portraiture in ancient Egypt}}
[[File:Retrato femenino (26771127162).jpg|thumb|Most likely a posthumous painted portrait of Cleopatra VII of Ptolemaic Egypt with [[red hair]] and her distinct facial features, wearing a royal [[diadem]] and pearl-studded hairpins, from Roman [[Herculaneum]], Italy, 1st century AD{{sfnp|Walker|Higgs|2001|pp=314–315}}{{sfnp|Fletcher|2008|pp=87, 246–247, see image plates and captions}}<ref group="note">{{harvnb|Fletcher|2008|p=87}} describes the painting from [[Herculaneum]] further: "Cleopatra's hair was maintained by her highly skilled hairdresser Eiras. Although rather artificial looking wigs set in the traditional tripartite style of long straight hair would have been required for her appearances before her Egyptian subjects, a more practical option for general day-to-day wear was the no-nonsense '[[Greco-Roman hairstyle|melon hairdo]]' in which her natural hair was drawn back in sections resembling the lines on a melon and then pinned up in a bun at the back of the head. A trademark style of [[Arsinoe II]] and [[Berenice II|Berenike II]], the style had fallen from fashion for almost two centuries until revived by Cleopatra; yet as both traditionalist and innovator, she wore her version without her predecessor's fine head veil. And whereas they had both been [[blonde]] like [[Alexander the Great|Alexander]], Cleopatra may well have been a [[redhead]], judging from the portrait of a flame-haired woman wearing the royal diadem surrounded by [[Ancient Egyptian art|Egyptian motifs]] which has been identified as Cleopatra."</ref>]]

In his triumphal procession at Rome in 29 BC, Octavian paraded Cleopatra's children Alexander Helios and Cleopatra Selene II, but he also presented an effigy to the crowd depicting Cleopatra with an asp clinging to her.{{sfnp|Roller|2010|pp=149, 153}}{{sfnp|Anderson|2003|p=56}}{{sfnp|Burstein|2004|p=66}} This was likely the same painting discovered in emperor [[Hadrian's Villa]] in 1818, now lost but described in an archaeological report and [[:File:Cleopatra_VII,_steel_engraving_of_the_encaustic_painting_found_at_Hadrian%27s_Villa_in_1818.jpg|depicted]] in a [[steel engraving]] by [[John Sartain]].{{sfnp|Pratt|Fizel|1949|pp=14–15}}{{sfnp|Sartain|1885|pp=41, 44}} However, the poet [[Propertius]], an eyewitness of Octavian's triumph along the [[Via Sacra]], noted that the paraded image of Cleopatra contained multiple snakes biting each of her arms.{{sfnp|Gurval|2011|p=60}}{{sfnp|Curran|2011|p=116}} Citing Plutarch, Giuseppe Pucci indicates that the effigy may have even been a statue.{{sfnp|Pucci|2011|p=202}} In his "Notes isiaques I" (1989), French Archaeologist [[:fr:Jean-Claude Grenier (égyptologue)|Jean-Claude Grenier]] observed that an ancient [[Roman portraiture|Roman statue]] of a woman wearing a [[Tyet|knot of Isis]] in the [[Vatican Museums]] portrays a snake crawling up her right breast, perhaps a depiction of Cleopatra's suicide while dressed as the [[Egyptian goddess]] [[Isis]].{{sfnp|Pucci|2011|pp=202–203, 207 footnote 28}}

A mid-1st century BC [[Roman art|Roman wall painting]] from [[Pompeian Styles|Pompeii]] most likely [[:File:Venus and Cupid from the House of Marcus Fabius Rufus at Pompeii, most likely a depiction of Cleopatra VII.jpg|depicting Cleopatra with her infant son Caesarion]] was walled off by its owner around 30 BC, perhaps in reaction to Octavian's proscription against images depicting Caesarion, the rival heir of Julius Caesar.{{sfnp|Roller|2010|p=175}}{{sfnp|Walker|2008|pp=35, 42–44}} Although statues of Mark Antony were torn down, those of Cleopatra were generally spared this program of destruction, including the one erected by Caesar in the [[Temple of Venus Genetrix]] in the [[Forum of Caesar]].{{sfnp|Roller|2010|pp=72, 151, 175}}{{sfnp|Varner|2004|p=20}} An [[:File:Roman Wall painting from the House of Giuseppe II, Pompeii, 1st century AD, death of Sophonisba, but more likely Cleopatra VII of Egypt consuming poison.jpg|early 1st century AD painting from Pompeii]] most likely depicts the suicide of Cleopatra, accompanied by attendants and even her son Caesarion wearing a royal diadem like his mother, although an asp is absent from the scene, perhaps reflecting the different causes of death provided in [[Roman historiography]].{{sfnp|Roller|2010|pp=148–149, 178–179}}{{sfnp|Elia|1956|pp=3–7}}<ref group="note">For further information about the painting in the House of Giuseppe II (i.e. Joseph II) at Pompeii and the possible identification of Cleopatra as one of the figures, see {{harvnb|Pucci|2011|pp=206–207, footnote 27}}</ref>

The story of the asp was widely accepted among the [[Augustan literature (ancient Rome)|Augustan-period]] [[Latin poetry|Latin poets]] such as [[Horace]] and [[Virgil]], in which two snakes were even suggested as biting Cleopatra.{{sfnp|Anderson|2003|p=56}}{{sfnp|Roller|2010|pp=148–149}}{{sfnp|Gurval|2011|pp=61–69, 74}} Although retaining the negative views of Cleopatra apparent in other pro-Augustan [[Roman literature]],{{sfnp|Roller|2010|pp=8–9}} Horace depicted Cleopatra's suicide as a bold act of defiance and liberation.{{sfnp|Gurval|2011|pp=65–66}} Virgil established the view of Cleopatra as a figure of epic [[melodrama]] and romance.{{sfnp|Gurval|2011|pp=66–70}}

===Medieval, Renaissance, and Baroque periods===
{{Multiple image
|total_width=450
|image1=Tomb of Cleopatra and Mark Antony, illuminated manuscript of Boccaccio, miniature by the Boucicaut master, 1409 AD (cropped).jpg
|image2=Woodcut illustration of Cleopatra and Mark Antony - Penn Provenance Project.jpg
|footer=Left: a [[Miniature (illuminated manuscript)|miniature illustration]] by the [[Boucicaut Master]] in the 1409 AD [[illuminated manuscript]] of [[Giovanni Boccaccio]]'s ''Des cas de nobles hommes et femmes'', depicting [[Mark Antony]] and Cleopatra in their tomb, with an asp slithering near her chest and a bloody sword impaling his{{sfnp|Anderson|2003|pp=53–54}} {{pb}}Right: ''The Banquet of Cleopatra and Antony'', a [[woodcut]] from a 1479 version of [[Giovanni Boccaccio]]'s ''[[De Mulieribus Claris]]'' published in [[Ulm]], Germany{{sfnp|Anderson|2003|p=50}}
}}

The story of Cleopatra's suicide by snakebite was often depicted in [[Medieval art|Medieval]] and [[Renaissance art]]. In a [[Miniature (illuminated manuscript)|miniature]] of a 1409 AD [[illuminated manuscript]] of the 14th-century AD poet [[Giovanni Boccaccio]]'s ''Des cas de nobles hommes et femmes'', the [[Boucicaut Master]] [[:File:Tomb of Cleopatra and Mark Antony, illuminated manuscript of Boccaccio, miniature by the Boucicaut master, 1409 AD (cropped).jpg|depicted Cleopatra and Antony lying together]] in a [[International Gothic|Gothic-style]] tomb, with a snake near Cleopatra's chest and a bloody sword through Antony's chest.{{sfnp|Anderson|2003|pp=53–54}} Illustrated versions of Boccaccio's written works, including images of Cleopatra and Antony committing suicide, first appeared in France during the [[Quattrocento]] (i.e. 15th century AD), authored by [[Laurent de Premierfait]].{{sfnp|Anderson|2003|p=51}} [[Woodcut]] illustrations of Boccaccio's ''[[De Mulieribus Claris]]'' published at [[Ulm]] in 1479 and [[Augsburg]] in 1541 depict Cleopatra's discovery of Antony's body after his suicide by stabbing.{{sfnp|Anderson|2003|pp=50–52}}

Like much of [[Medieval literature]] about Cleopatra, Boccaccio's writings are largely negative and misogynistic. However, they were countered by the 14th-century poet [[Geoffrey Chaucer]], who offered a positive view of Cleopatra.{{sfnp|Anderson|2003|pp=51–54}} Chaucer began his [[hagiography]] [[The Legend of Good Women|on virtuous pagan women]] with the life of Cleopatra, depicted in a satirical fashion as a queen engaged in [[courtly love]] with her knight Mark Antony.{{sfnp|Gurval|2011|pp=73–74}}{{sfnp|Jones|2006|pp=214–215}} However, Chaucer's depiction of her suicide included a pit of serpents rather than the Roman tale of the asps.{{sfnp|Gurval|2011|p=74}}{{sfnp|Jones|2006|pp=221–222}}

[[File:Cleopatra - Michelangelo Buonarroti.png|thumb|upright|left|''Cleopatra'', by [[Michelangelo]], c. 1535]]
During the [[Italian Renaissance]], free-standing nude depictions of Cleopatra poisoned by an asp were common.{{sfnp|Anderson|2003|p=60}} The 16th-century [[Venetian school (art)|Venetian artist]] Giovanni Maria Padovano (i.e. Mosca) created two marble reliefs of the suicide of Antony and Cleopatra, as well as various free-standing nude statues of Cleopatra being bitten by the asp that were partly inspired by ancient [[Roman sculpture]]s such as the ''[[Esquiline Venus]]''.{{sfnp|Anderson|2003|pp=56–59}}<ref group="note">As outlined by {{harvnb|Pina Polo|2013|pp=186, 194 footnote 10}}, {{harvnb|Roller|2010|p=175}}, {{harvnb|Anderson|2003|p=59}}, scholars debate whether or not the ''[[Esquiline Venus]]''—discovered in 1874 on the [[Esquiline Hill]] in Rome and housed in the [[Palazzo dei Conservatori]] of the [[Capitoline Museums]]—is a depiction of Cleopatra, based on the [[commons:Category:Esquiline Venus (Musei Capitolini)|hairstyle and facial features]] of the woman in the sculpture, her apparent royal diadem worn over the head, and the [[uraeus]] [[Egyptian cobra]] wrapped around a vase or column at the base. As explained by {{harvnb|Roller|2010|p=175}}, the ''Esquiline Venus'' is generally thought to be a mid-1st century AD [[Interpretatio graeca|Roman copy]] of a 1st century BC Greek original from the school of [[Pasiteles]].</ref> [[Bartolommeo Bandinelli]] created a drawing of Cleopatra as a free-standing nude committing suicide that served as the basis for a similar engraving by [[Agostino Veneziano]].{{sfnp|Anderson|2003|p=60}} Another engraving by Veneziano and a drawing by [[Raphael]] depicting Cleopatra's suicide as she slumbered were inspired by the ancient [[Greco-Roman]] ''[[Sleeping Ariadne]]'', which at the time was thought to depict Cleopatra.{{sfnp|Anderson|2003|pp=60–61}}{{sfnp|Pucci|2011|p=203}} Works of the [[French Renaissance]] also depict Cleopatra slumbering while pressing a snake to her breast.{{sfnp|Anderson|2003|p=61}} [[Michelangelo]] created a black-chalk drawing of Cleopatra's suicide by asp bite around 1535.{{sfnp|Anderson|2003|p=62}} The 17th-century [[Baroque]] painter [[Guido Reni]] [[:File:Guido Reni - Cleopatra - WGA19301.jpg|depicted Cleopatra's death]] by asp bite, although the snake depicted is tiny compared to a real Egyptian cobra.{{sfnp|Gurval|2011|p=59}}

The ''Sleeping Ariadne'', acquired by [[Pope Julius II]] in 1512, inspired the composition of [[Renaissance literature]]: three poems that were eventually carved into the [[pilaster]] frame of the statue.{{sfnp|Curran|2011|pp=114–116}} The first of these poems was published by [[Baldassare Castiglione]], which became widely circulated by 1530 and inspired the other two by [[Bernardino Baldi]] and [[Agostino Favoriti]].{{sfnp|Curran|2011|p=116}} Castiglione's poem depicted Cleopatra as a tragic but honorable ruler in a doomed love affair with Antony, a queen whose death freed her from the ignominy of Roman imprisonment.{{sfnp|Curran|2011|pp=116–117}} The ''Sleeping Ariadne'' was also commonly depicted in paintings, including those by [[Titian]], [[Artemisia Gentileschi]], and [[Edward Burne-Jones]].{{sfnp|Pucci|2011|p=203}} These works tended to [[Erotic art|eroticize]] the moment of Cleopatra's death, while [[Victorian era]] artists found the unconscious, recumbent female form as an acceptable outlet for their eroticism.{{sfnp|Pucci|2011|p=203}}
{{multiple image|total_width=600
|image1=Michele di ridolfo (scuola), suicidio di cleopatra, 1560 ca. 02.JPG
|image2=Guido Reni - Cleopatra - WGA19301.jpg
|image3=Alessandro Turchi - The death of Cleopatra.jpg
|footer=''The Death of Cleopatra'', by [[Michele Tosini]], c. 1560 (left); ''Cleopatra'', by [[Guido Reni]], 1638-1639{{sfnp|Gurval|2011|p=59}} (center); ''The Death of Cleopatra'', by [[Alessandro Turchi]], c. 1640 (right).
}}

Cleopatra's death is featured in various works of the performing arts. In the 1607 [[Play (theatre)|play]] ''[[Devil's Charter]]'' by [[Barnabe Barnes]], a [[snake handler]] brings the two asps to Cleopatra and allows them to bite both her breasts in a racy manner.{{sfnp|Anderson|2003|p=62}} In [[William Shakespeare]]'s 1609 play ''[[Antony and Cleopatra]]'' the snake represents both death as well as a lover who Cleopatra desires, yielding to his pinch.{{sfnp|Anderson|2003|p=62}} Shakespeare relied on [[Thomas North]]'s 1579 translation of Plutarch for crafting his play, which can be viewed as both a comedy and a tragedy.{{sfnp|Jones|2006|p=223}} The play involved use of multiple asps, as well as the character of Charmion who killed herself by asp bite after Cleopatra.{{sfnp|Jones|2006|pp=233–234}}

===Modern era===
In modern literature, [[Ted Hughes]]' poem "Cleopatra to the Asp" (1960) creates a monologue of Cleopatra speaking to the asp that is about to kill her.{{sfnp|Jones|2006|pp=303–304}} During the Victorian era, plays such as ''Cléopâtre'' (1890) by [[Victorien Sardou]] became popular, although audiences were generally shocked by the emotional intensity of stage actress [[Sarah Bernhardt]]'s depiction of Cleopatra reacting to Antony's suicide.{{sfnp|DeMaria Smith|2011|p=165}} In opera, [[Samuel Barber]]'s ''[[Antony and Cleopatra (opera)|Antony and Cleopatra]]'', first performed in 1966 and based on Shakespeare's play, Cleopatra recounts a dream that Antony, now dead before her, would become emperor of Rome.{{sfnp|Martin|2014|pp=16–17}} When [[Publius Cornelius Dolabella (suffect consul 35 BC)|Dollabella]] informs her that Caesar intends to march her in his triumph in Rome, she commits suicide with Charmion by asp bite, before being carried off to be buried with Antony.{{sfnp|Martin|2014|p=17}}
[[File:The Death of Cleopatra.JPG|thumb|upright|left|''The Death of Cleopatra'', by [[Edmonia Lewis]], 1876{{sfnp|Pucci|2011|pp=201–202}}]]

In cinema, the character of Cleopatra had appeared in forty-three different films by the end of the 20th century.{{sfnp|Pucci|2011|p=195}} [[Georges Méliès]]' ''[[Robbing Cleopatra's Tomb]]'' ({{lang-fr|Cléopâtre}}), an 1899 French [[Silent film|silent]] horror film, was the first film to depict the character of Cleopatra.{{sfnp|Jones|2006|p=325}} Following the [[Italo-Turkish War]] (1911–1912), the 1913 [[Cinema of Italy|Italian film]] ''[[Antony and Cleopatra (1913 film)|Marcantonio e Cleopatra]]'' by [[Enrico Guazzoni]] depicted Cleopatra as the embodiment of the cruel [[Orient]], a queen who had defied Rome, while the actions of her lover Antony, after his suicide, are forgiven by Octavian.{{sfnp|Pucci|2011|pp=203–204}} In cultivating a stage persona for her character in the 1917 US film ''[[Cleopatra (1917 film)|Cleopatra]]'', actress [[Theda Bara]] was seen in public petting snakes while the [[Fox Film Corporation]] posed her in front of Cleopatra's alleged [[Ancient Egyptian funerary practices|mummified remains]] in a museum, where she announced that she was the reincarnation of Cleopatra, having received [[Egyptian hieroglyphs|hieroglyphic]] tributary offerings from a reincarnated servant.{{sfnp|Wyke|Montserrat|2011|p=178}} Fox Studios also had Bara dress as a leader of the occult and associated her with perverse [[Death drive|death and sexuality]].{{sfnp|Wyke|Montserrat|2011|p=178}} The 1963 Hollywood film ''[[Cleopatra (1963 film)|Cleopatra]]'' by [[Joseph L. Mankiewicz]] contains a dramatic scene where the Egyptian queen, portrayed by [[Elizabeth Taylor]], is engaged in a slap-fight with her lover Mark Antony, portrayed by [[Richard Burton]], inside the tomb where they would be interred.{{sfnp|Wyke|Montserrat|2011|p=190}}

In other modern visual arts, Cleopatra has been depicted in mediums such as paintings and sculptures. In her 1876 sculpture ''The Death of Cleopatra'', African American artist [[Edmonia Lewis]], despite championing the non-white female form in artworks, chose to depict Cleopatra with [[Caucasian race|Caucasian features]], perhaps in keeping with Cleopatra's recorded lineage as a [[Ancient Macedonians|Macedonian Greek]].{{sfnp|Pucci|2011|pp=201–202}}<ref group="note">{{harvnb|Pucci|2011|p=201}} affirms that "to give Cleopatra a white complexion is quite correct, given her Macedonian descent. In literature, however, Cleopatra's racial features are more ambiguous." <br>For Cleopatra's European origins through her ancestor [[Ptolemy I Soter]], a general of [[Alexander the Great]] from the kingdom of [[Macedon]]ia in [[northern Greece]], see {{harvnb|Fletcher|2008|pp=1, 23}} and {{harvnb|Southern|2009|p=43}}.</ref> Lewis' [[Neoclassical sculpture]] offers a [[Post-mortem interval|post-mortem]] view of Cleopatra dressed in Egyptian regalia and sitting on her throne, which is decorated with two [[sphinx]] heads that represent the twins she bore with Mark Antony: Alexander Helios and Cleopatra Selene II.{{sfnp|Smithsonian American Art Museum}} An 1880 [[commons:Category:Cleopatra by Charles Gauthier|plaster sculpture of Cleopatra committing suicide]], now found in [[Lille]], France, was once thought to be a work by [[Albert Darcq]], but a restoration and cleaning of the sculpture revealed the signature of [[Charles Gauthier]], to whom the work is now attributed.{{sfnp|The Art Tribune}} The 1874 painting ''Death of Cleopatra'' by [[Jean-André Rixens]] depicts a dead Cleopatra with very light skin, accompanied by [[Handmaiden|maidservants]] with rather dark skin, a combination frequently found in modern artworks portraying the scene of Cleopatra's death.{{sfnp|Manninen|2015|p=221, footnote 11}} [[Orientalist painting]]s by Rixens and others influenced the hybrid Ancient-Egyptian and Middle-Eastern decor found in the [[J. Gordon Edwards]]' film ''Cleopatra'' starring Bara, seen standing on a [[Persian carpet]] but with [[Art of ancient Egypt|Egyptian wall paintings]] in the background.{{sfnp|Sully|2010|p=53}}

